Description: Scientific Materials Corporation is committed to the production of the highest quality low-loss laser materials.
Full Description: Scientific Materials Corporation is committed to the production of the highest quality low-loss laser materials. Back in 1960, researchers were engaged in cutting edge quantum physics aimed at building a “coherent light machine” based on a 1958 theoretical paper, "Infrared and optical masers,” by two scientists at the famed Bell Labs in New Jersey. Despite enormous sums of money and the efforts of top physicists from around the world, no one had yet built a working model, and doubts were growing that such a machine was possible. Meanwhile, at Hughes Aircraft in California, a poorly funded junior physicist named Ted Maiman was trying the unconventional approach of utilizing a single crystal solid state material as the ‘quantum engine’ for the device. He asked Ralph Hutcheson, then at Union Carbide, to produce the world’s first optical-quality laser rod from Ruby crystal. On May 16, 1960, Dr. Maiman stunned the world by creating the first LASER, using Ralph’s rods.[1],[2],[3] This invention launched one of the most broad reaching technologies of the 20th century. The uses and applications of lasers have revolutionized scientific research ranging from the smallest quantum particles to the scale of the universe. From rock concerts, to next generation medical procedures; from optical communications at the ‘speed of light’, to the military’s most advanced sensing and weaponry systems, lasers are everywhere in daily life. In the years following the invention of the laser, the quality of laser crystals became a limiting factor to the growth of the laser industry. In 1989, after more than three decades in the laser materials industry, Ralph Hutcheson founded a company in Bozeman Montana near the campus of Montana State University dedicated to the development and growth of the world’s highest quality single-crystal laser materials. He succeeded, and the company he founded, Scientific Materials Corporation, was acquired by FLIR Systems in 2005.

Description: Suncore Photovoltaic Technology Company Limited is the leader in Concentrated Photovoltaic(CPV) technology
Full Description: Suncore Photovoltaics Technology Co. Ltd (SPT), headquartered in Huainan City, Anhui Province, China, is a vertically integrated and world-recognized supplier of concentrator photovoltaic (CPV) equipment including modules, trackers, complete systems, EPC services, and project financing. SPT is also an experienced provider of utility-scale solar power systems and a project developer with more than 120MW of CPV systems deployed worldwide. With over 2,000,000sq/ftft. of manufacturing facility, Suncore is capable of deploying more than 200MW CPV systems per year. In addition to system manufacturing capabilities, Suncore also hosts a state of the art automated CPV receiver manufacturing line providing CPV components to many CPV companies worldwide.  Suncore Photovoltaics, Inc. (SPI), founded in 2010, is a wholly owned US based subsidiary for SPT located in Albuquerque New Mexico. SPI employs an extremely seasoned and knowledgeable R&D engineering team covering everything from new product development to long term reliability and system monitoring. In addition to R&D and engineering activities, SPI also spearheads Suncore’s global sales and project development efforts providing competitive solar solutions to the worldsworld’s sunniest locations.  Suncore has been dedicated to the manufacturing and commercialization of CPV since 2007. Suncore holds over a dozen patents for its ground mounted utility scale CPV systems with new innovative IP being generated each year. In addition to the ground mounted utility CPV system, Suncore has acquired other technology and IP allowing further penetration into the global solar market. In 2013 Suncore acquired Zenith Solar the creator of a revolutionary Combined Heat & Power (CHP) technology which allows for the production of both electricity and hot water in a single system. Suncore’s CHP product will primarily be used for the distributed generation market.
